  "outcome": {
    "conformal_wins": "tie",
    "verdict": "TIE at the top of a tight distribution-free cluster. Six distribution-free methods (jackknife+ 0.0018, Mondrian/weighted conformal 0.0037, naive-global 0.0040, split conformal 0.0042, CQR 0.0054) are statistically indistinguishable in mean coverage error (all paired-bootstrap delta CIs among them straddle 0), and the best committed conformal method (Mondrian) is NOT separable from the strongest non-conformal baseline (quantile regression, 0.0049): mondrian_vs_QR delta CI [-0.0034,+0.0023] includes 0. So conformal does NOT beat every prior-art method \u2014 quantile regression, itself a distribution-free adaptive method, ties it. BUT the committed conformal layer SIGNIFICANTLY beats the two genuinely parametric/Bayesian-approx priors: parametric Gaussian miscovers by 6.7pp at 80% (delta CI [-0.038,-0.015], excludes 0), and a naive Gaussian ensemble-variance interval collapses to ~8% coverage (delta CI [-0.789,-0.777]). Efficiency (contested axis): CQR did NOT Pareto-dominate the incumbent \u2014 at ~equal coverage its 90% interval is significantly WIDER than split conformal (+0.028 log2FC, CI [+0.0278,+0.0291]); the adaptive-width methods buy no sharpness here because the residual distribution is near-homoscedastic in these 4 leakage-safe features. AURC (selective prediction): all methods sit in a narrow 0.112-0.120 band far above the 0.048 oracle and near the 0.118 random line; trust-ordering skill is modest and no method's ordering is meaningfully better than another's. Conditional coverage over baseMean deciles: Mondrian shows no advantage (it conditions on culture_condition, not baseMean); parametric Gaussian's apparently-good worst slice is an artifact of global over-coverage (wider intervals), not real adaptivity.",
    "honest_headline": "Under real donor shift, distribution-free calibration (conformal AND quantile-regression) is decisively better-calibrated than parametric/Bayesian-approx UQ, which miscovers badly. Within the distribution-free family the committed conformal layer is at parity with the field \u2014 it neither wins nor loses. The theoretically-expected result (conformal is robust under shift) is confirmed; the honest null is that conformal buys no measurable calibration OR sharpness edge over quantile regression on this surface.",
    "tautology_guard_respected": "Verdict headlines the contested axes (magnitude of parametric miscoverage, CQR width Pareto-loss, AURC), not 'conformal hits coverage'.",
    "pre_declared_win": false
  },
